{
  "ANOVA is used to compare:": "",
  "Two proportions": "",
  "Two means only": "",
  "Three or more group means": "",
  "Variances only": "",
  "ANOVA (Analysis of Variance) extends the two-sample t-test to compare means across three or more groups simultaneously.": "",
  "The null hypothesis in one-way ANOVA states:": "",
  "At least one mean differs": "",
  "All group means are equal": "",
  "All means are different": "",
  "Variances differ across groups": "",
  "H-null in ANOVA states that all population group means are equal. The alternative states that at least one mean differs.": "",
  "The F-statistic equals:": "",
  "n - 1": "",
  "MSB / MSW": "",
  "SSB + SSW": "",
  "MSW / MSB": "",
  "F = MSB/MSW = between-group variability divided by within-group variability. A large F suggests groups differ more than expected by chance.": "",
  "A large F-value indicates:": "",
  "All means are equal and there is no detectable variation between the different group averages": "",
  "Sample size is too small to produce meaningful differences between the group means being compared": "",
  "Between-group differences are large relative to within-group variability": "",
  "The model is incorrect because the assumptions of the analysis have been seriously violated": "",
  "A large F means group means differ more than would be expected from random within-group variation alone, suggesting at least one group mean is different.": "",
  "If F is close to 1, this suggests:": "",
  "Between-group and within-group variability are similar, providing little evidence against H-null": "",
  "Strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis that all group means are equal in the population": "",
  "All means are definitely different from one another, requiring pairwise follow-up comparisons": "",
  "The test has failed due to insufficient variation within the groups being compared in the study": "",
  "When F is near 1, between-group variation is about the same as within-group variation, suggesting the groups do not differ more than expected by chance.": "",
  "ANOVA assumes:": "",
  "Independent samples, approximate normality, and equal variances": "",
  "No assumptions are required because ANOVA is a nonparametric test that works with any data type": "",
  "Dependent samples where each individual appears in more than one treatment group simultaneously": "",
  "Non-normal data that follows a uniform or heavily skewed distribution across all of the groups": "",
  "Standard one-way ANOVA requires three key assumptions: independent observations, approximately normal distributions within each group, and equal variances (homoscedasticity).": "",
  "Degrees of freedom for MSB in one-way ANOVA with k groups equals:": "",
  "n - k": "",
  "k - 1": "",
  "k": "",
  "Between-group degrees of freedom = number of groups minus 1 = k - 1.": "",
  "Degrees of freedom for MSW in one-way ANOVA with k groups and n total observations equals:": "",
  "Within-group degrees of freedom = total observations minus number of groups = n - k.": "",
  "SST = SSB + SSW means:": "",
  "Degrees of freedom add up to n": "",
  "Sum of means equals the total": "",
  "F = SSB / SSW": "",
  "Total variation equals between-group plus within-group variation": "",
  "Total variability (SST) is partitioned into two components: variation between group means (SSB) and variation within groups (SSW).": "",
  "If ANOVA yields a p-value of 0.001, this means:": "",
  "The F-statistic equals 0": "",
  "Fail to reject H-null": "",
  "All means are definitely identical": "",
  "Strong evidence that at least one group mean differs": "",
  "A very small p-value (0.001) provides strong evidence against the null hypothesis that all group means are equal.": "",
  "What does MSB (Mean Square Between) measure?": "",
  "How much the group means differ from the overall grand mean": "",
  "The residual error": "",
  "The total variation in the data": "",
  "Individual data spread within each group": "",
  "MSB = SSB / (k-1) quantifies between-group variability. It measures how spread out the group means are from the overall mean.": "",
  "What does MSW (Mean Square Within) measure?": "",
  "The between-group spread": "",
  "The total variation in the dataset": "",
  "Differences between group means": "",
  "The average variability of observations within each group": "",
  "MSW = SSW / (n-k) is the pooled within-group variance. It estimates the common variance within groups, assuming equal variances.": "",
  "What are post-hoc tests and when are they used?": "",
  "Tests run before ANOVA to check assumptions": "",
  "Tests that replace ANOVA entirely": "",
  "Pairwise comparison tests used after ANOVA rejects H-null, to identify which specific groups differ": "",
  "Tests for checking normality of the data": "",
  "When ANOVA rejects H-null, it only tells us that at least one mean differs but not which one. Post-hoc tests (like Tukey's HSD) perform pairwise comparisons to pinpoint which groups differ.": "",
  "What does Tukey's HSD (Honestly Significant Difference) do?": "",
  "Tests whether data are normally distributed": "",
  "Tests for equal variances across groups": "",
  "Replaces the ANOVA test entirely": "",
  "Provides pairwise comparisons of all group means while controlling the family-wise error rate": "",
  "Tukey's HSD compares every pair of group means after a significant ANOVA, adjusting for multiple comparisons to keep the overall Type I error rate at the desired level.": "",
  "Why is running multiple t-tests instead of ANOVA problematic?": "",
  "t-tests are always more powerful than ANOVA": "",
  "Multiple pairwise t-tests inflate the overall Type I error rate": "",
  "ANOVA is less accurate than multiple t-tests": "",
  "It gives the same result as ANOVA": "",
  "With k groups, there are k(k-1)/2 possible pairwise comparisons. Each t-test has its own chance of a Type I error, and these compound, greatly inflating the overall false positive rate.": "",
  "What does 'two-way ANOVA' test?": "",
  "Two factors and their possible interaction": "",
  "Three group means only": "",
  "Only within-group variation": "",
  "One factor only": "",
  "Two-way ANOVA examines two independent variables (factors) simultaneously, testing for main effects of each factor and their interaction effect.": "",
  "What does 'interaction effect' mean in two-way ANOVA?": "",
  "The factors are completely independent of each other": "",
  "No main effects exist in the model": "",
  "The effect of one factor depends on the level of the other factor": "",
  "The model is incorrectly specified": "",
  "An interaction means the combined effect of two factors differs from the sum of their individual effects. For example, a drug's effect might depend on whether the patient is male or female.": "",
  "What does the ANOVA table display?": "",
  "Only the regression intercept and its standard error for the baseline group in the analysis": "",
  "SS, df, MS, F-statistic, and p-value for each source of variation": "",
  "Only the group means and their sample standard deviations for each treatment being compared": "",
  "Only the p-value from the overall F-test without any intermediate computational details": "",
  "The ANOVA table organizes all key statistics: sum of squares (SS), degrees of freedom (df), mean squares (MS), the F-statistic, and the p-value for between-group and within-group sources.": "",
  "What does 'homogeneity of variance' mean in ANOVA?": "",
  "All group means must be equal": "",
  "The population variances of all groups are assumed to be equal": "",
  "The sample sizes must be equal": "",
  "The data must be normally distributed": "",
  "Homogeneity of variance (also called homoscedasticity) is the assumption that all groups have the same population variance. Levene's test can be used to check this assumption.": "",
  "What does 'eta-squared' measure in ANOVA?": "",
  "The proportion of total variance explained by the group membership (effect size)": "",
  "The number of groups in the analysis": "",
  "The within-group standard deviation": "",
  "The p-value of the F-test": "",
  "Eta-squared = SSB/SST represents the proportion of total variance accounted for by group differences. It serves as an effect size measure for ANOVA.": "",
  "A psychologist tests three therapy methods (CBT, medication, combined) on depression scores. With 20 patients per group (60 total) and k = 3 groups, how many degrees of freedom does MSB have?": "",
  "57": "",
  "2": "",
  "59": "",
  "3": "",
  "df(between) = k - 1 = 3 - 1 = 2. The within-group df would be n - k = 60 - 3 = 57.": "",
  "A farmer tests four fertilizers on crop yield. The ANOVA table shows SSB = 450, SSW = 900, with k = 4 groups and n = 40 total plants. What is the F-statistic?": "",
  "15.00": "",
  "2.00": "",
  "6.00": "",
  "0.50": "",
  "MSB = SSB/(k-1) = 450/3 = 150. MSW = SSW/(n-k) = 900/36 = 25. F = MSB/MSW = 150/25 = 6.00.": "",
  "A company compares employee satisfaction across five departments. After ANOVA yields F = 4.32 with p = 0.003, Tukey's HSD reveals that only the Marketing and IT departments differ significantly. What can the company conclude?": "",
  "The ANOVA must be wrong because only two groups differ": "",
  "All five departments have different satisfaction levels": "",
  "Post-hoc tests should not have been performed": "",
  "Only Marketing and IT have significantly different mean satisfaction scores; the other departments do not differ significantly from each other": "",
  "ANOVA's rejection of H-null means at least one pair differs. Tukey's HSD identified the specific pair (Marketing vs. IT). It is common for ANOVA to reject H-null even when only one pair of groups drives the difference.": "",
  "A researcher studies the effect of exercise type (running, swimming, cycling) and diet (low-carb, balanced) on weight loss using two-way ANOVA. The interaction between exercise and diet is significant (p = 0.02). What does this mean?": "",
  "Exercise and diet each independently affect weight loss with no connection": "",
  "The model is invalid and should be discarded": "",
  "The effect of exercise type on weight loss depends on the diet; for example, running may produce more weight loss with low-carb but not with balanced diet": "",
  "Exercise type and diet have no effect on weight loss": "",
  "A significant interaction means the effect of one factor depends on the level of the other. The best exercise type for weight loss may vary depending on which diet a person follows.": "",
  "A teacher compares test scores across four sections of the same course. ANOVA gives F = 1.12 with p = 0.35. At alpha = 0.05, what should the teacher conclude?": "",
  "Post-hoc tests should be performed": "",
  "At least one section has significantly different scores": "",
  "There is not enough evidence to conclude that mean scores differ across sections": "",
  "All sections have exactly the same mean score": "",
  "Since p = 0.35 > alpha = 0.05, we fail to reject H-null. F = 1.12 is close to 1, suggesting little difference between sections. Post-hoc tests are not warranted when ANOVA fails to reject.": "",
  "A nutritionist compares calorie intake across three age groups. She has 15, 18, and 12 participants in the groups respectively (n = 45 total). If SSB = 12,000 and SSW = 36,000, what is the F-statistic?": "",
  "3.50": "",
  "0.33": "",
  "7.00": "",
  "14.00": "",
  "MSB = 12,000/(3-1) = 6,000. MSW = 36,000/(45-3) = 36,000/42 = 857.14. F = 6,000/857.14 = 7.00.": "",
  "A botanist measures plant growth under three light conditions. One group has a clearly non-normal distribution with a small sample of 8 plants. What should the botanist consider?": "",
  "Use a chi-square test instead": "",
  "Remove the non-normal group from the analysis": "",
  "Use a nonparametric alternative like the Kruskal-Wallis test": "",
  "Proceed with ANOVA since it requires no assumptions": "",
  "ANOVA assumes approximate normality, and with a small sample (n = 8), the test is not robust to violations. The Kruskal-Wallis test is a nonparametric alternative that does not require normality.": "",
  "An ANOVA with k = 4 groups and n = 60 yields SSB = 300 and SST = 1500. What is eta-squared, and how would you interpret it?": "",
  "Eta-squared = 0.20; group membership explains 20% of the total variance": "",
  "Eta-squared = 0.50; half the variance is explained": "",
  "Eta-squared = 5.0; this is a very large effect": "",
  "Eta-squared = 0.80; group membership explains 80% of the variance": "",
  "Eta-squared = SSB/SST = 300/1500 = 0.20. This means 20% of the total variance in the outcome is explained by group membership, which is a medium-to-large effect in many fields.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company tests three drug dosages (low, medium, high) on blood pressure reduction. ANOVA yields p = 0.008. Tukey's HSD shows: Low vs. Medium (p = 0.42), Low vs. High (p = 0.005), Medium vs. High (p = 0.03). Which pairs differ significantly at alpha = 0.05?": "",
  "All three pairs differ significantly": "",
  "Low vs. High and Medium vs. High differ significantly, but Low vs. Medium does not": "",
  "No pairs differ significantly": "",
  "Only Low vs. High differs significantly": "",
  "Low vs. High (p = 0.005 < 0.05) and Medium vs. High (p = 0.03 < 0.05) are both significant. Low vs. Medium (p = 0.42 > 0.05) is not. The high dose produces significantly different results from both other doses.": "",
  "A sports scientist measures reaction time for athletes in three sports (soccer, basketball, tennis) at two times of day (morning, evening) using two-way ANOVA. Results show: Sport main effect (p = 0.001), Time main effect (p = 0.15), Interaction (p = 0.72). What should the scientist report?": "",
  "Only sport type significantly affects reaction time; time of day and the interaction are not significant": "",
  "None of the effects are statistically significant": "",
  "Sport type and time of day both significantly affect reaction time": "",
  "The interaction is significant, so main effects cannot be interpreted": "",
  "At alpha = 0.05: Sport (p = 0.001) is significant, Time (p = 0.15) is not, and the interaction (p = 0.72) is not. The sport an athlete plays matters for reaction time, but time of day does not, and the effect of sport does not depend on time of day.": ""
